2500|$|The National Farmers Unions of England and Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland {{immediately}} {{responded in}} a joint statement expressing their amazement and giving detailed figures to refute his argument. At this Clement Attlee asked for Evans' resignation, dismissing him from office after only six weeks. Evans stuck by his opinions even though [...] "the National Farmers' Unions have <b>my</b> <b>scalp</b> under their belt". He later denied as [...] "fantastic" [...] rumours {{that he intended to}} resign his Parliamentary seat. On 16 May Evans used a debate on the Finance Bill to set out a full defence of his charges against agriculture.|$|E
