5000|$|During the War of 1812 {{he fought}} {{on the side}} of the United States despite his {{advanced}} age. He participated in the Battle of Fort George in 1813, and in the Battle of Lundy's Lane in 1814. Following that battle a story is related that an Indian allied with the British (variously Chippewa or Mohawk) came to the Seneca saying he was deserting. Hhe was identified as a spy, and Farmer's Brother said to him [...] "here are my rifle, my tomahawk, and <b>my</b> <b>scalping</b> knife: take your choice by which you will die." [...] The spy chose the rifle and indicated he wanted to be shot through the heart (or head), so Farmer's Brother immediately pointed his rifle there and killed him.|$|R
